	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Debate on onion tariffs in Senegal intensifies amid onion glut on West African markets </h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 August 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>&nbsp;In June 2012, Mamadou Ba, chairperson of the inter-professional organisation for onion, called on the Senegalese government to ‘stop the import of onions for three years’, in view of the marketing problems faced by local onion producers. According to press reports, national production of onions is currently 240,000 tonnes, but ‘demand for imported onions is bigger than the demand for… local onions’.</p><p>In response, the president of Senegal endorsed calls for the reorganisation of the onion market, including through the establishment of ‘a special protective measure’ to address competition from imports. This needs to be seen against the background of the government announcement in May 2012 that it aimed to promote horticulture production in order to reduce imports by 50%.</p><p>These calls followed the emergence of an onion glut on certain West African markets, most notably that of Niger. Following good prices in the previous season, production grew by 20% in the current season, which led to prices collapsing and farmers being unable to clear their debt. According to press reports, ‘with an average annual production of 500,000 tonnes, Niger is the leading producer of onions in the West African Economic and Monetary Union area’. Over 70% of Niger’s onion crop is exported to Côte d'Ivoire, Ghana, Benin and Togo.</p><p>The situation in Niger has been compounded by increased supplies on regional markets from Burkina Faso, Mali and the Netherlands. In May 2012, the government of Niger began exploring scope for public purchasing of onions to ease price pressures, expansion of storage facilities and improving the marketing of onions.</p><p>Similar initiatives to strengthen the functioning of onion supply chains are taking place in Senegal with the national union of manufacturers and traders in Senegal (UNACOIS) signing an agreement in May 2012 to put all local onion production at an agreed price of between €0.33/kg €0.42/kg and €0.50/kg, according to quality.</p><p>Dutch onion exports to Russia declined by 90% in the first 4 months of 2012 (compared to the same period in 2011), and their exports to Senegal declined by 9%. Dutch onion exports to West African markets as a whole rose by 13% in the period. This compares to the 23% increase in Dutch onion exports to Senegal in 2011 compared to 2010 (totalling 134 million kg in 2011).&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
